nlikely(!(X))) {					\<br />&gt; -		printk(KERN_ERR "\n");				\<br />&gt; +		cut_here();					\<br />&gt;  		printk(KERN_ERR "AFS: Assertion failed\n");	\<br />&gt;  		BUG();						\<br /><br />Instead of doing that "cut_here()" thing, you should either use the WARN() <br />thing that has a format string already, or we should extend BUG() to have <br />that kind of thing too. So in this case I think that you should use WARN() <br />instead, ie change it to be<br /><br />	#define ASSERT(x) do {						\<br />		if (WARN(X, "AFS: Assertion failed"))		\<br />			do_exit(SIGSEGV);				\<br />	} while (0)<br /><br />instead. And yes, in the long run, I really think we should just extend <br />the current BUG() reporting to have that kind of semantics, but I think <br />your "cut_here()" thing is a horrible hack.<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
